               167                                                              
               168 class SkyCoord(ShapedLikeNDArray):                           
               169     """High-level object providing a flexible interface for  
            celestial coordinate                                                
               170     representation, manipulation, and transformation between 
            systems.                                                            
               171                                                              
               172     The `SkyCoord` class accepts a wide variety of inputs for
            initialization. At                                                  
               173     a minimum these must provide one or more celestial       
            coordinate values with                                              
               174     unambiguous units.  Inputs may be scalars or             
            lists/tuples/arrays, yielding                                       
               175     scalar or array coordinates (can be checked via          
            ``SkyCoord.isscalar``).                                             
               176     Typically one also specifies the coordinate frame, though
            this is not                                                         
               177     required. The general pattern for spherical              
            representations is::                                                
               178                                                              
               179       SkyCoord(COORD, [FRAME], keyword_args ...)             
               180       SkyCoord(LON, LAT, [FRAME], keyword_args ...)          
               181       SkyCoord(LON, LAT, [DISTANCE], frame=FRAME, unit=UNIT, 
            keyword_args ...)                                                   
               182       SkyCoord([FRAME], <lon_attr>=LON, <lat_attr>=LAT,      
            keyword_args ...)                                                   
               183                                                              
               184     It is also possible to input coordinate values in other  
            representations                                                     
               185     such as cartesian or cylindrical.  In this case one      
            includes the keyword                                                
               186     argument ``representation_type='cartesian'`` (for        
            example) along with data                                            
               187     in ``x``, ``y``, and ``z``.                              
               188                                                              
               189     See also: https://docs.astropy.org/en/stable/coordinates/
               190                                                              
               191     Examples                                                 
               192     --------                                                 
               193     The examples below illustrate common ways of initializing
            a `SkyCoord`                                                        
               194     object.  For a complete description of the allowed syntax
            see the                                                             
               195     full coordinates documentation.  First some imports::    
               196                                                              
               197       >>> from astropy.coordinates import SkyCoord  #        
            High-level coordinates                                              
               198       >>> from astropy.coordinates import ICRS, Galactic,    
            FK4, FK5  # Low-level frames                                        
               199       >>> from astropy.coordinates import Angle, Latitude,   
            Longitude  # Angles                                                 
               200       >>> import astropy.units as u                          
               201                                                              
               202     The coordinate values and frame specification can now be 
            provided using                                                      
               203     positional and keyword arguments::                       
               204                                                              
               205       >>> c = SkyCoord(10, 20, unit="deg")  # defaults to    
            ICRS frame                                                          
               206       >>> c = SkyCoord([1, 2, 3], [-30, 45, 8], frame="icrs",
            unit="deg")  # 3 coords                                             
               207                                                              
               208       >>> coords = ["1:12:43.2 +31:12:43", "1 12 43.2 +31 12 
            43"]                                                                
               209       >>> c = SkyCoord(coords, frame=FK4, unit=(u.hourangle, 
            u.deg), obstime="J1992.21")                                         
               210                                                              
               211       >>> c = SkyCoord("1h12m43.2s +1d12m43s",               
            frame=Galactic)  # Units from string                                
               212       >>> c = SkyCoord(frame="galactic", l="1h12m43.2s",     
            b="+1d12m43s")                                                      
               213                                                              
               214       >>> ra = Longitude([1, 2, 3], unit=u.deg)  # Could also
            use Angle                                                           
               215       >>> dec = np.array([4.5, 5.2, 6.3]) * u.deg  # Astropy 
            Quantity                                                            
               216       >>> c = SkyCoord(ra, dec, frame='icrs')                
               217       >>> c = SkyCoord(frame=ICRS, ra=ra, dec=dec,           
            obstime='2001-01-02T12:34:56')                                      
               218                                                              
               219       >>> c = FK4(1 * u.deg, 2 * u.deg)  # Uses defaults for 
            obstime, equinox                                                    
               220       >>> c = SkyCoord(c, obstime='J2010.11',                
            equinox='B1965')  # Override defaults                               
               221                                                              
               222       >>> c = SkyCoord(w=0, u=1, v=2, unit='kpc',            
            frame='galactic',                                                   
               223       ...              representation_type='cartesian')      
               224                                                              
               225       >>> c = SkyCoord([ICRS(ra=1*u.deg, dec=2*u.deg),       
            ICRS(ra=3*u.deg, dec=4*u.deg)])                                     
               226                                                              
               227     Velocity components (proper motions or radial velocities)
            can also be                                                         
               228     provided in a similar manner::                           
               229                                                              
               230       >>> c = SkyCoord(ra=1*u.deg, dec=2*u.deg,              
            radial_velocity=10*u.km/u.s)                                        
               231                                                              
               232       >>> c = SkyCoord(ra=1*u.deg, dec=2*u.deg,              
            pm_ra_cosdec=2*u.mas/u.yr, pm_dec=1*u.mas/u.yr)                     
               233                                                              
               234     As shown, the frame can be a                             
            `~astropy.coordinates.BaseCoordinateFrame`                          
               235     class or the corresponding string alias.  The frame      
            classes that are built in                                           
               236     to astropy are `ICRS`, `FK5`, `FK4`, `FK4NoETerms`, and  
            `Galactic`.                                                         
               237     The string aliases are simply lower-case versions of the 
            class name, and                                                     
               238     allow for creating a `SkyCoord` object and transforming  
            frames without                                                      
               239     explicitly importing the frame classes.                  
               240                                                              
               241     Parameters                                               
               242     ----------                                               
               243     frame : `~astropy.coordinates.BaseCoordinateFrame` class 
            or string, optional                                                 
               244         Type of coordinate frame this `SkyCoord` should      
            represent. Defaults to                                              
               245         to ICRS if not given or given as None.               
               246     unit : `~astropy.units.Unit`, string, or tuple of        
            :class:`~astropy.units.Unit` or str, optional                       
               247         Units for supplied coordinate values.                
               248         If only one unit is supplied then it applies to all  
            values.                                                             
               249         Note that passing only one unit might lead to unit   
            conversion errors                                                   
               250         if the coordinate values are expected to have mixed  
            physical meanings                                                   
               251         (e.g., angles and distances).                        
               252     obstime : time-like, optional                            
               253         Time(s) of observation.                              
               254     equinox : time-like, optional                            
               255         Coordinate frame equinox time.                       
               256     representation_type : str or Representation class        
               257         Specifies the representation, e.g. 'spherical',      
